Hi Team, can you help validate this issue?

The function [bson_value_copy |https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/master/src/libbson/src/bson/bson-value.c#L39]is vulnerable to a buffer overflow on heap allocated memory.
When the function is used with a value_type of {{BSON_TYPE_UTF8}}it will use the [v_utf8.len|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/master/src/libbson/src/bson/bson-types.h#L313] which is a {{uint32_t}} passed to malloc (+1 for null byte) and then memcpy.
The vulnerable function looks like [this|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/master/src/libbson/src/bson/bson-value.c#L39] :
{code:java}
void bson_value_copy (const bson_value_t *src, bson_value_t *dst)
{
   BSON_ASSERT (src);
   BSON_ASSERT (dst);

   dst->value_type = src->value_type;

   switch (src->value_type) {
   case BSON_TYPE_DOUBLE:
      dst->value.v_double = src->value.v_double;
      break;
   case BSON_TYPE_UTF8:
      dst->value.v_utf8.len = src->value.v_utf8.len;
      dst->value.v_utf8.str = bson_malloc (src->value.v_utf8.len + 1); // INTEGER OVERFLOW HERE
      memcpy (dst->value.v_utf8.str, src->value.v_utf8.str, dst->value.v_utf8.len); //MEMORY CORRUPTION
      dst->value.v_utf8.str[dst->value.v_utf8.len] = '\0';
      break;
{code}
The problem is that if the utf8 that is parsed has a length of UINT_MAX, then malloc will allocate {{src->value.v_utf8.len + 1}} so {{UINT_MAX +1}} which because the variable is a {{uint32_t}} will overflow and be equal to 0.
Then memcpy will try to copy UINT_MAX bytes into this newly allocated memory of "0 bytes".
h2. Fix ideas:
 - A simple check that the len is not equal to UINT_MAX, as only this value is problematic.
 - Use size_t but I understand that goes against the current design choice of the entire lib.

h2. Steps To Reproduce:

I have attached to this report a .c PoC file as well as a shell script `c.sh´.
{code:java}
1. Download the provided assets
2. Install mongoc with libbson [Mongo C driver](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/languages/c/c-driver/current/libmongoc/tutorials/obtaining-libraries/installing/)
3. Execute the c.sh script, this will simply start the compilation of the PoC
4. Execute ./PoC, you'll observe a segmentation fault. If you look at the source code you'll see that the output confirms the memory corruption happening in bson_value_copy.
{code}
Here's a screenshot reproducing those steps:
{F3621078}
h2. Impact

Memory corruption with arbitrary data from an attacker.
Has the potential to affect confidentiality, availability and especially integrity, as this is a library the exact impacted components will depend on the usage but in the worst case all three component can be critically affected leading to all kinds of consequences as the attacker can pretty much manipulate the entire heap memory of the process to their own liking with very little restriction.

Hi Team, can you help validate this issue? According to the POC a "malicious" server would need to be involved in order for the attack to succeed. I am wondering how easy is it for this attack to be successful as I am assuming that the connection must first be established. The POC:
{panel}
There is an integer overflow vulnerability in the {{mcd_rpc_message_decompress}} function which is used in compressed communication between the mongoc client and the mongo server.
A malicious server can force the mongoc client to copy arbitrary attacker controlled data into either a heap memory region which was allocated without enough bytes or at the 0x0 address.
The problematic code can be observed [here|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/master/src/libmongoc/src/mongoc/mongoc-cluster.c#L3603] :
{code:java}
   const size_t message_header_length = 4u * sizeof (int32_t);

   const size_t uncompressed_size = (size_t) mcd_rpc_op_compressed_get_uncompressed_size (rpc);

   //                                                   INTEGER OVERFLOW HERE
   const size_t original_message_length = message_header_length + uncompressed_size; 
   uint8_t *const ptr = bson_malloc (original_message_length);

{...}

   // Populate the msgHeader fields.
   {
      uint32_t storage;

      memcpy (&storage, &message_length, sizeof (storage));
      storage = BSON_UINT32_TO_LE (storage);
      memcpy (ptr + 0, &storage, sizeof (storage));
{...}
{code}
The problem here is the addition of {{const size_t original_message_length = message_header_length + uncompressed_size;}} which is later used in bson_malloc() to determine the number of bytes to allocate. After that the pointer is filled (memcpy) with msgHeader fields which are also sent by the malicious server and therefore attacker controlled.
The math behind the overflow :
{{message_header_length + uncompressed_size;}}
{{message_header_length}} is a fixed value which is equal to the size of 4 int32_t (16bytes).
{{uncompressed_size}} is sent by the server so as an attacker we can supply the value of our choosing.
Therefore if we send {{0xffffffff - 16 = 0xfffffff0}} as the {{uncompressed_size}} our addition results in 0. bson_malloc allocates 0 bytes (in reality bson_malloc is implemented to return NULL in this specific case) and there is no NULL checks after so we directly go to the memcpy.
For the second case scenario with a buffer too small being allocated. We need to send between {{0xfffffff1}} and {{0xffffffff}} as the \{{uncompressed_size}}and malloc will receive 1 to 15 bytes as a parameter but a lot more (minimum 16bytes) will be copied to that buffer.
An additional observation is that the attacker doesn't need to actually send 0xfffffff0 bytes of data as the client will just take the given size and perform the malloc and memcpy regardless, the actual_uncompressed size check comes at the end of the function after the memory corruption has already happen.
You can find the exact packets that the malicious server will send in the header file provided with this PoC, they were elaborated by observing a normal network interaction between {{mongoc}} and {{mongod}} and modifying the bytes representing {{uncompressed_size}} according to the mongo protocol.
h2. Steps To Reproduce:

I've attached to this report two c source code files (one for the mongoc client and one for the malicious server), there is also a header file used by the server code and a c.sh script to compile the client.
For simplicity I've also provided a .zip with all these files if you prefer.
 # Install the [Mongo C driver library|https://www.mongodb.com/docs/languages/c/c-driver/current/libmongoc/tutorials/obtaining-libraries/installing/]
 # Unzip the provided archive or download all the files into a folder.
 # Compile the client (./c.sh) and the server (gcc -o server server.c)

 # Execute the server ( ./server ) then execute the PoC ( ./PoC). You will observe the NULL pointer dereference.

Here's a screnshot the PoC :
{F3585340}
h2. Fix ideas :

Do not allow {{uncompressed_size}} to be between [0xfffffff0 and 0xffffffff].
h2. Impact

The impact is either a direct remote crash of the client or a remote memory corruption with at minimum 16 attacker controlled bytes of data.
