h4. Summary
In my tests, I created a document to pass on to a bulk write using the {{let}} option. I then add an update operation to the bulk write which uses a variable defined in {{let}}. When the document exceeds a size of 91 bytes (e.g. by using {{a}} as the key and repeating {{a}} 79 times), the resulting command document no longer includes the {{let}} option.

h4. Environment
Reproduced in 1.30, but pretty sure it affects 2.x as well.

h4. How to Reproduce
See above. This is the PHP code that triggers this:
{code}
$document = ['a' => str_repeat('a', 78)]; // Passes
$document = ['a' => str_repeat('a', 79)]; // Fails

$bulk = new MongoDB\Driver\BulkWrite(['let' => ['testDocument' => $document]]);
$bulk->update(['_id' => 1], [['$set' => ['document' => '$$testDocument']]], ['upsert' => true]);
$manager->executeBulkWrite(NS, $bulk);
{code}

h4. Additional Background

Example:
{code}
#define macro_without_args() 123
#define macro_with_args(a, b) a + b

int x;
x = MLIB_IS_EMPTY(nonmacro);           // OK.
x = MLIB_IS_EMPTY(macro_without_args); // OK.
x = MLIB_IS_EMPTY(macro_with_args);    // error: too few arguments provided to function-like macro invocation.
{code}

This may risk breaking builds for users if existing macros are defined. Discovered when working on CDRIVER-4489 when trying to invoke:
{code}
mlib_duration(1, min)
{code}

{{min}} was defined as a macro accepting two arguments

*Scope* Omit the "CXX=" from the handshake if "MONGOC_CXX_COMPILER_ID" is an empty string (to signal no check was made)

*Background & Motivation* The CXX string was added in CDRIVER-6091. Quoting https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/pull/2114:

{quote}
If a C++ compiler is not found, {{CXX=Unknown}} is included. Alternatively: {{CXX}} could be omitted if not detected. But I expect it may help with analysis to easily distinguish between: "driver too old to check" and "checked and did not find".
{quote}

PHP does not check for a C++ compiler. Suggested in [this comment|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/pull/1900/changes/BASE..25badf5b5816fa33d892622a5e6cf010422d17c3#r2619912972] to use an empty string to indicate "did not check". Since including "CXX=" is not really helpful (and adds data to the limited size handshake), this ticket proposes excluding "CXX=" when empty.

*Proposal*

Try to send {{killCursors}} on client-side cursor timeout

*Background & Motivation*

The C driver deliberately does not re-establish connection to send {{killCursors}} to the server in [_mongoc_client_kill_cursor|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/blob/b4984965877d559862e225beba09cb4e9d4a56a6/src/libmongoc/src/mongoc/mongoc-client.c#L2153].

[CSOT suggests|https://github.com/mongodb/specifications/blob/master/source/client-side-operations-timeout/client-side-operations-timeout.md#cursor-close-methods-refresh-timeoutms] it is OK to extend the timeout to send {{{}killCursors{}}}:
{quote}If a cursor times out client-side (e.g. a non-tailable cursor created with {{{}timeoutMode=CURSOR_LIFETIME{}}}), it’s imperative that drivers make a good-faith effort to close the server-side cursor even though the timeout has expired because failing to do so would leave resources open on the server for a potentially long time. It was decided that {{timeoutMS}} will be refreshed for {{close}} operations to allow the cursor to be killed server-side.
{quote}
CSOT is a large project and not-yet implemented in the C driver. This ticket proposes a smaller change to improve a timeout caused by {{{}socketTimeoutMS{}}}.

Here is a [failing test|https://github.com/mongodb/mongo-c-driver/compare/master...kevinAlbs:mongo-c-driver:HELP-83560] that shows {{killCursors}} is not sent after a client-side timeout (even though the cursor ID was returned by the server):
{code:java}
mongoc_cursor_t *cursor =
   mongoc_collection_aggregate(coll, MONGOC_QUERY_NONE, pipeline, tmp_bson("{'batchSize': 1 }"), NULL);

// First document returned fast:
ASSERT(mongoc_cursor_next(cursor, &got));
ASSERT(mongoc_cursor_get_id(cursor)); // Cursor established.

// Second document triggers timeout:
ASSERT(!mongoc_cursor_next(cursor, &got));
ASSERT(mongoc_cursor_error(cursor, &error));
ASSERT_ERROR_CONTAINS(error, MONGOC_ERROR_STREAM, MONGOC_ERROR_STREAM_SOCKET, "socket error or timeout");

mongoc_cursor_destroy(cursor); // Does not send killCursors!
{code}

The sample code for {{withTransaction}} does not set an explicit session for the calls to {{{}mongoc_collection_insert_one{}}}. This means these write operations are not actually part of the transaction. To associate these write operations with the transaction, the session ID should be passed as part of the {{opts}} argument.

Additionally, the sample code passes the {{reply}} argument to the {{mongoc_collection_insert_one}} calls, but that is not the intended use of the parameter. The {{bson_t}} that {{reply}} points to is {{{}NULL{}}}, then the callback can choose to construct a {{bson_t}} if propagating a reply is desired. To be clear, this code isn't incorrect, but passing {{*reply}} to write operations when it is actually {{NULL}} is misleading. In most cases, passing {{NULL}} _explicitly_ as the reply is suitable.

All in all, sample code that looks like this:
{code:java}
ret = mongoc_collection_insert_one(coll, doc, NULL, *reply, error); {code}
should be amended to look like this:
{code:java}
bson_t *opts = bson_new();
BSON_ASSERT(mongoc_client_session_append(session, opts, error));

ret = mongoc_collection_insert_one(coll, doc, opts, NULL, error);

bson_free(opts);{code}

{{bson_t}} can use {{bson_impl_inline_t}} or {{bson_impl_alloc_t}} to store BSON data. {{bson_impl_inline_t}} can store a small BSON data on the stack. {{bson_impl_alloc_t}} refers to a heap-allocated BSON data.

{{bson_impl_alloc_t}} has a self-referencing pointer {{buf}}. This means it is not trivially relocatable:

{code:c}
static void
test_bson_not_trivially_relocatable (void)
{
   bson_t bad;
   {
      bson_t heap_allocated = BSON_INITIALIZER;

      // Force a heap allocation:
      BSON_APPEND_UTF8 (&heap_allocated,
                        "key",
                        "placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-"
                        "placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-placeholder-");
      ASSERT (!(heap_allocated.flags & BSON_FLAG_INLINE)); // Heap-allocated.

      // Intended to transfer ownership from `heap_allocated` to `bad`:
      bad = heap_allocated;

      // `bad` refers to memory in `heap_allocated`!
      void *addr = ((bson_impl_alloc_t *) &bad)->buf;
      ASSERT_CMPVOID (addr, >=, &heap_allocated);
      ASSERT_CMPVOID (addr, <=, &heap_allocated + sizeof (heap_allocated));
   }

   // `heap_allocated` out of scope.
   bson_iter_t bad_iter;
   ASSERT (bson_iter_init_find (&bad_iter, &bad, "key")); // Might crash!
}
{code}

As a result, a memcpy of a {{bson_t}} is invalid for the heap-allocated case (but OK for the stack allocated case). This may not be immediately obvious. And it has been the cause of previous bugs: CDRIVER-6112.

Related discussion: https://docs.google.com/document/d/121Oc5VQdHZ63PS62gDWozt8FbCKrK_MRe-iJUNmoCfM/edit?disco=AAABTKt-EVI

